[5] Regional cooperation: Mekong countries (ACMECS)
Date: Thu, 3 Nov 2005
From: Dunya Selenic Minet <minet@loxinfo.co.th>
Source: Bangkokpost News, 3 Nov 2005 [edited]
<http://www.bangkokpost.com/breaking_news/breakingnews.php?id=59603>


The leaders of Thailand and 4 neighbouring countries agreed today in
Bangkok to cooperate in containing the spread of bird flu, which has
already claimed 58 lives in the region.

One of the main outcomes of the 2nd summit of the Ayeyawady-Chao
Phraya-Mekong Economic Cooperation Strategy (ACMECS) -- named for the
3 rivers that connect its members: Cambodia, Laos, Burma, Thailand
and Vietnam -- was a joint commitment to combat avian influenza and
other infectious diseases.

"This declaration on avian flu is an expression of our determination
to mount a strong, concerted effort to contain the spread of this
disease in the region by enhancing surveillance and response systems,
sharing information and capacity building of public health
personnel," Thai Prime Minister Thaksin Shinawatra said.

To do so, Thailand has pledged 2.5 million dollars in seed money to
go toward anti-bird flu projects, he added.

The summit came nearly 2 years after the 1st human bird-flu deaths
began to be reported. Nearly all of the 62 human deaths have occurred
in the region: 41 in Vietnam, 13 in Thailand and 4 in Cambodia. [The
remaining 4 deaths occurred in Indonesia. - Mod.AS]

The leaders at the one-day summit also agreed to promote contract
farming, integration as a tourist destination requiring only a single
visa and the setting up of "One Stop Services" at customs checkpoints
to facilitate border trade among the neighbours.

This year's ACMECS summit drew Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen, Lao
Prime Minister Bounnhang Vorachith, Burmese Prime Minister and Lt Gen
Soe Win, and Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van Khai.

The 1st ACMECS Summit was held in Pagan, Burma, 2 years ago. This
year, Vietnam joined the new forum.

--
Dr Dunya Selenic Minet
Veterinary surgeon, Bangkok
<minet@loxinfo.co.th>
